body:
The error message provided when attempting to implement a const generic trait on (), does not explain the problem well, and also provides an incorrect solution.

Playground link:
https://play.rust-lang.org/?version=stable&mode=debug&edition=2018&gist=9f13fd2b46d8fbcad14e57184d499b3e

```rust
trait HelloVoid<const VALUE: i32> {
    fn call(self) -> i32;
}

impl<const VALUE: i32> HelloVoid<VALUE> for () {
    fn call(self) -> i32 {
        println!("Hello, Void!");
        
        VALUE
    }
}

fn main() {
    let value = ().call();
    println!("{}", value);
}
```

The current output is:

```
   Compiling playground v0.0.1 (/playground)
error[E0282]: type annotations needed
  --> src/main.rs:14:20
   |
14 |     let value = ().call();
   |                    ^^^^ cannot infer the value of const parameter `VALUE` declared on the trait `HelloVoid`
   |
help: consider specifying the const argument
   |
14 |     let value = ().HelloVoid::<VALUE>();
   |                    ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^

error: aborting due to previous error

For more information about this error, try `rustc --explain E0282`.
error: could not compile `playground`

To learn more, run the command again with --verbose.
```

Ideally the output should look like:

```
error[E0282]: type annotations needed
  --> src/main.rs:14:20
   |
14 |     let value = ().call();
   |                    ^^^^ cannot infer the value of const parameter `VALUE` declared on the trait `HelloVoid`
   |
help: consider specifying the const argument
14 |     <() as HelloVoid<Value>>::call(())
   |        ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
```

The error should also reference the () type that the trait is impl'd for.
